1) Importing and Processing the Data¶

Our dataset, collected via FRED website, is a time series data tracking the Georgia Housing index from 2000 to 2019.

The dependent variable of the study is the Housing Index, where we investigate what factors may play a bigger role in affecting the change of the index.

The independent of the study includes:

  1. New Private Housing Units - The number of new private housing established
    (measures the average price changes for homes that are sold or refinanced)
  2. Median Household Income - The median household income in Georgia
  3. Unemployment Rate - The unemployment rate in Georgia
  4. All employee, Social Assistance - The number of employee hired in Social Assistance sector in thousand of person
    (As an indicator to measure the growth of the Social Assistance sector in GA)
  5. All employee, Education, Health Service - The number of employee hired in Education and Health sector in thousand of person
    (As an indicator to measure the growth of the Education, Health Service sector in GA)
Variables Description
New Private Housing Units The number of new private housing established
Median Household Income The median household income in Georgia
Unemployment Rate The unemployment rate in Georgia
All employee, Social Assistance The number of employee hired in Social Assistance sector in thousand of person
All employee, Education, Health Service The number of employee hired in Education and Health sector in thousand of person

We also create a new dataframe houseDiff to calculate the difference between each rows. We can later utilize this dataframe to conduct regression analysis of change of our independent variables

In [7]:
# create a copy the original dataframe
houseDiff = house.copy()
# write a for-loop to calculate the difference and add it to the new dataframe
for i in range(0, len(house)):
    if i == 0:
        houseDiff["Housing Index"][i] = 0
        houseDiff["New Private Housing Units"][i] = 0
        houseDiff["Unemployment rate"][i] = 0
        houseDiff["All employee, Social Assistance "][i] = 0
        houseDiff["All Employee, Education, Health Service"][i] = 0
        houseDiff["Median Household Income"][i] = 0
    else:
        houseDiff["Housing Index"][i] = houseDiff["Housing Index"][i] - house["Housing Index"][i - 1]
        houseDiff["New Private Housing Units"][i] = houseDiff["New Private Housing Units"][i] - house["New Private Housing Units"][i - 1]
        houseDiff["Unemployment rate"][i] = houseDiff["Unemployment rate"][i] - house["Unemployment rate"][i - 1]
        houseDiff["All employee, Social Assistance "][i] = houseDiff["All employee, Social Assistance "][i] - house["All employee, Social Assistance "][i - 1]
        houseDiff["All Employee, Education, Health Service"][i] = houseDiff["All Employee, Education, Health Service"][i] - house["All Employee, Education, Health Service"][i - 1]
        houseDiff["Median Household Income"][i] = houseDiff["Median Household Income"][i] - house["Median Household Income"][i - 1]
houseDiff.head().round(3)

Data Visualization¶

Before conducting any regression analysis, let's first inpect the data set to a further extent! With the housing index as the dependent variable, we have to find some linear relationships with our regressors by implementing scatter plots. These variables are further used for building our regression models. For statistical visualizations, we used seaborn and matplotlib as the main workhorse.

Since personal assetthe is a major factor that influence us whether to own a house or not, We suspect that there might be a strong correlation between the median household income and the housing index.

The graph shows that there is indeed a similar positive trend between these two variables. One interesting fact that is worth notice is that before the intersection in 2010, there is a period of time where the housing index continues to rise depite the lowlevel household income, suggesting that people might purchase houses in a irrational level that exceeds their budget during that time.

Results¶

From the regression analysis we can get the following model:

$$ Medium house index = 0.001houseIncome - 7.904unemployRate - 3.913socialAssistance + 3.398healthService + 276.216$$

We can also dissect the model to examine the individual factor effect on the medium house index when controllling for other factors:

  • houseIncome: an unit increase in houseIncome leads to 0.001 increase in the Medium house index
  • unemployRate: an one percertage point increase in unEmployment rate leads to 7.904 decrease in the medium house index
  • socialAssistance: a thousand increase in number of people in social assistance decreases the medium house index by 3.913
  • healthService: a thousand increase in the number of people in health service increases the medium house index by 3.398
  • intercept: when all factors are zero, the medium house index is 276.216

The model also provides an $$R^2 = 0.631$$ which means that about 63.1% of the variations in the response variable can be explained by the independent variables.

Nevertheless, this doesn't mean that each factor is significant in this regression model. From the table we see that only unemployRate, healthService, and Intercept pass the least significance threshold (p < 0.1), and only unemployRate pass the highest significance threshold (p < 0.01). Therefore, the regression model indicates that while number of people in health service and unemployment rate are influencial for the medium house index, unemployment rate is the most statistically significant factor in determining the variation in the medium house index.

Discussion¶

In this project we exmaine possible factors influencing the change in the medium housing index in Georgia (GA), United States. From the regression model we discovered that only unemployment rate in GA is the most statistically significant factors in the regression model. This is reasonable as we normally use the unemployment rate as an indicator of the purchasing power of the consumers. Hence, it's rational that as unemployment rate goes up, the medium housing index decreases since sellers would want to lower the price to sell more houses.

Future studies should expand factors of interest such as population of the state, distance relative to central cities, etc. The analysis can also be conducted in state-level. For example, compare the medium housing price between states of low GDP and states of high GDP. In addition, we can also conduct cross-sectional analysis study between countries to examine larger factors such as GDP, export, etc., and how do these factors influence the outcome of housing index.
